[09:12] <brrt> i figured out a better solution
[09:12] <brrt> one that doesn't need stack or walking at all
[09:12] <brrt> see
[09:13] <brrt> all that we are after is the location of the return address into the JIT frame
[09:14] <brrt> by processor semantics, we know exactly where that is going to be placed; 8 bytes down from the position of %rsp, at the point where we do the call instructoin
[09:15] <brrt> provided we never do a push or pop, which is easy to ensure, we know exactly what that is, because it is completely under our control
[09:19] <jnthn> :)
[09:20] <brrt> we also don't need to walk the stack, and we also don't need to keep the frame pointer arround. this solution has literally no drawbacks at all
[09:23] <brrt> so the idea is to take a pointer to where I know the return address will be, and assign that to a field in the threadcontext. this field will then also function as a reliable way to answer 'are we currently executing in the JIT'
